  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraper (fetchers → filters → SQLite dedup store → notifiers). There's no React/frontend code in this repo, so I'm skipping that section rather than force-fitting it — the closest analog (redundant per-item recomputation) is covered under \"redundant computations\" below.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nThe dedup loop issues one `SELECT` **and** one `INSERT`/`UPDATE` per job, sequentially:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nWith Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix/Google each paginating into the thousands of postings, a single pipeline run can issue several thousand individual round-trips to SQLite instead of a handful. Fix: batch-load existing hashes once, then use `executemany` for writes.\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's variable limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update(cur.execute(q, chunk).fetchall())\n\n    new, changed, touched, inserts, updates = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job); inserts.append(row)\n        elif prev_hash != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n            changed.append(job); updates.append(row)\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if inserts:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,:source,...,:now,:now)\"\"\", inserts)\n    if updates:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", updates)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(n) round trips into O(n/900 + 3).\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`_compile()` recompiles every include/exclude regex **for every job**, because `match()` calls it and `filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n```\n\nFor a run with thousands of fetched jobs and several keyword rules, that's thousands of redundant `re.compile` calls. Fix: compile once outside the loop and pass compiled patterns in.\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in (rules.get(\"locations\") or [])]\n\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n(and change `match()`'s signature to accept pre-compiled patterns instead of calling `_compile` internally).\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `models.py:66-76` (`Job.content_hash`)\n\n`content_hash` is a plain `@property` that re-hashes on every access. In the changed-job path, `Store.diff` reads `job.content_hash` once for comparison, then `_update`/`_insert` call `job.to_row()`, which computes it again — a second SHA-256 over the same string per changed/new job. Since `Job` uses `@dataclass(slots=True)`, `functools.cached_property` won't work directly (no `__dict__`), but you can add an explicit slot:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _hash_cache: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._hash_cache is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._hash_cache = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode()).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._hash_cache\n```\n\nLow-impact at current volumes, but free once the batching fix above is in place (same `to_row()` call site benefits).\n\n### 4. Memory usage — `Job.raw`\n\nEvery `Job` carries the full raw ATS payload in `raw: dict` for the life of the pipeline run (only dropped in `to_row()` right before persisting). For big boards (Amazon/Microsoft return thousands of postings with verbose JSON), that's the dominant memory cost of a run. Not a leak — it's all released when `run()` returns — but if you ever keep a `Store`/pipeline object alive across multiple scans (e.g., a long-lived service instead of a one-shot CLI), be aware `raw` is the thing to drop early. No action needed today given the current one-shot CLI usage pattern.\n\n### 5. Caching opportunities\n\n- **Meta fetcher** (`fetchers.py:537-574`) re-fetches and re-parses the whole `metacareers.com/jobs` HTML page every run just to scrape `lsd`/`__spin_*` tokens, which don't change within a session. If you ever run multiple scans back-to-back in one process, these could be cached with a short TTL to save a page fetch, but for the current 12h-cron single-shot model it's not worth the complexity.\n- **`agent.py cmd_db_new`** (`agent.py:64-102`): `store.added_since(since)` pulls *all* rows past the watermark via `fetchall()`, then groups/truncates in Python to `DUMP_LIMIT`. On a first run across many newly-added sources this can materialize far more rows than are ever emitted. If that becomes a real cost, push a `LIMIT` into the SQL using a window big enough to guarantee full `first_seen` groups (e.g. `LIMIT limit * 2`), falling back to the full scan only if the boundary lands mid-group.\n\n### Priority\n\n1. **Fix `Store.diff`'s N+1 pattern** — biggest real win, scales with total postings across all ATS sources (easily 5–10k per run once Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix/Google are all configured).\n2. **Hoist regex compilation out of `filter_jobs`** — cheap fix, removes O(n × rules) recompilation.\n3. Everything else is minor at current scale; revisit only if job volume or run frequency grows significantly.\n",
